comment: Global offset is -1.4 to compensate glass-supported homing procedure. Cell-free test print. GelMA (T1) and HAMA (T2). Vol. T1: 500 µL (layer 1), + 100 µL (layer 3). Vol. T2: 400 µL (layer 2).  Washing channels: dipping, removing excess liquid with KimWipe (touching channels). Store in warm ECGM2 until further use.  T1 in layer 1 can be less ink (total netting of printhead), but in layer 3 was too little -> increase vol. there. Vol. of T2 OK but netting was not uniform centrally. All prints look good but 2/4 with missing part on short side because too little T1 vol. in layer 3. Channels visible macroscopically but not with microscope. Was HAMA really cured or channel structures only "burned" into GelMA?  All observed and discarded.

Global offset is -1.4 to compensate glass-supported homing procedure.  GelMA (T1) and HAMA (T2). Vol. T1: 400 µL (layer 1), + 300 µL (layer 3). Vol. T2: 450 µL (layer 2).  Washing channels: dipping, then rinsing 5x0.6 mL warm DPBS with pipette, removing excess liquid with KimWipe (touching channels). Store in warm ECGM2 until further use.  Super prints except number 6 (airbuuble in first in last layer.  Transferring all at the same time into separate 24-wells with 0.5 mL 1x Hase in ECGM2 +P/S (230429 AT).
